Diagram 3 (Correct)
[{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg949\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}{\f1\fmodern\fprq2\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}{\f2\froman\fprq2\fcharset129 \'b9\'d9\'c5\'c1;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1042\f0\fs18
\par It's an original idea to play dansu at 1. This move leaves black with no way to respond.
\par
\par \pard\nowidctlpar\qj If black captures at 2, white cuts black at 3 and black is unable to approach from either side. It is clever, isn't it? Instead of 2, if black plays at 3, white captures at \b\f1 A\lang1033\kerning2\f2\fs20
\par \pard\lang1042\kerning0\b0\f0\fs18 and black is still dead.
\par
\par \pard\nowidctlpar\qj Instead of 2, if black plays at \b\f1 A\b0\f0 , it is a good move for white to play dansu from the outside with \b\f1 B\b0\f0 . Black has no way to live.
\par }
